        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T20:03:51"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "act": "THE QUESTION",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "Why does the smallest semiclassical ellipse retain half a quantum of action instead of collapsing to a point?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T20:03:51"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "OLD RULE",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "The original Bohr-Sommerfeld rule set the closed action integral equal to n h. For n equals zero, that older rule would allow zero action.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T20:03:51"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "THE TARGET",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Exact quantum mechanics gives the harmonic-oscillator spectrum E n equals n plus one-half times h-bar omega. The semiclassical rule needs the same half-unit.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T20:03:51"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "TURNING POINTS",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "A bound orbit has two soft turning points. The oscillatory WKB wave inside must connect to decaying solutions outside, and those connections change the phase bookkeeping.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "trace"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T20:03:51"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "MASLOV CORRECTION",
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "For two ordinary soft turning points the closed orbit has Maslov index two. The invariant result is a half-unit correction to the action quantization; local pi-over-four descriptions are convention-dependent bookkeeping.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "reveal"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T20:03:51"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "act": "CORRECTED RULE",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "The corrected condition is the closed action integral equals n plus one-half times h. For the harmonic oscillator, this WKB condition happens to reproduce the exact energy spectrum.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "collapse"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T20:03:51"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "act": "GROUND PATCH",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "At n equals zero, the semiclassical action area is h over two. So the smallest ellipse remains finite, matching the exact zero-point energy h-bar omega over two.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "zoom"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T20:03:51"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "act": "SCOPE",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Do not reverse the logic: a phase-space ellipse is a semiclassical energy-shell picture, not the exact ground-state probability distribution. The exact nonzero energy also follows from operator methods and the uncertainty principle.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "build": {
